<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+4">Human Vision</font></font> </p>
<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+3">Human 
visual field: about 200 degrees of arc</font></font> <font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="6"><a href="visual-field.pdf"><img src="../../../Graphics%20Templates/Diamonds/Di-red.gif" alt="The linked PDF file shows the human visual field which comprisis about 100 degrees of arc for each eye. The area of overlap comprises about 60 degrees." border="0" height="11" width="11"></a></font></font>&nbsp; <br> 
<font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+3"><i>Fovea</i>(area of highest resolution): 
about 2 degrees of arc</font></font> <font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="6"><a href="acuity-distribution.pdf"><img src="../../../Graphics%20Templates/Diamonds/Di-red.gif" alt="The linked PDF file shows the distribution of acuity in the human visual field. There is a distinct peak in the fovea (center of the eye) that comprises only 2 degrees of arc" border="0" height="11" width="11"></a></font></font>&nbsp;<a href="acuity-letters.png"><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+2"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 11px; height: 11px;" src="../../../Graphics%20Templates/Diamonds/Di-red.gif" alt="The linked image shows the HCI lab of the Department of Information and Computer Science, University of California, Irvine"></font></font></a><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"></span><font face="Arial,Helvetica" size="+2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 75% of the human visual operations are related to the fovea.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Human vision is not like a camera; does not take a complete picture at once </font></font><font face="Arial,Helvetica" size="+2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"> </font></font><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="6"><a href="retina.mpg"><img src="../../../Graphics%20Templates/Diamonds/Di-red.gif" alt="The linked PDF file shows the physiology of the human eye." border="0" height="11" width="11"></a></font></font><font face="Arial,Helvetica" size="+2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><br>
</font></font></p>


<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+3">Light reception takes place in the 
<i>retina</i></font><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="6"><a href="eye-physiology.pdf"><img src="../../../Graphics%20Templates/Diamonds/Di-red.gif" alt="The linked PDF file shows the physiology of the human eye." border="0" height="11" width="11"></a></font><font size="+3">, 
which contains 2 types of photoreceptors:</font></font> <br> &nbsp; <table style="height: 112px; width: 730px;" border="1" cols="3"> 
<tbody><tr> <td style="width: 288px;"><br>
</td><td style="width: 170px;"><b><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+1">Cones</font></font></b></td><td style="width: 298px;"><b><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+1">Rods</font></font></b></td></tr> 
<tr> <td style="width: 288px;"><i><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+1">Mediated visual impression</font></font></i></td><td style="width: 170px;"><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+1">colors</font></font></td><td style="width: 298px;"><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size="+1">degrees 
